The issue with the original solution is that it incorrectly calculates the minimal difference between the total amounts of chocolates consumed by Irina and Mihaela. The original approach was to calculate a running sum and then take the absolute difference between Irina's consumption (from the start to some index) and Mihaela's consumption (from that index to the end). However, this doesn't take into account the rule that each girl must consume at least one chocolate bar and the chocolate bars must be contiguous.

To fix this, the algorithm should perform a two-pointer approach. One pointer starts at the beginning of the array, representing Irina's consumption, and the other pointer starts at the end of the array, representing Mihaela's consumption. These pointers move towards each other, stopping when they meet. At every step, we will calculate the difference in consumption and update the minimum difference as necessary.

Let's rewrite the solution accordingly:

```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_map>
#include <algorithm>
#include <limits>

int main() {
    std::ifstream in("ciocolata.in");
    std::ofstream out("ciocolata.out");
    
    int C, N;
    in >> C >> N;
    
    std::vector<int> chocolates(N);

    if (C == 1) {
        std::unordered_map<int, int> frequency;
        // Read chocolates' weights and calculate frequency
        for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
            in >> chocolates[i];
            frequency[chocolates[i]]++;
        }
        // Find the most common, smallest weight
        int most_common_weight = std::numeric_limits<int>::max(), max_frequency = 0;
        for (const auto &pair : frequency) {
            if (pair.second > max_frequency || (pair.second == max_frequency && pair.first < most_common_weight)) {
                most_common_weight = pair.first;
                max_frequency = pair.second;
            }
        }
        out << most_common_weight << '\n';
    } else {
        // Read chocolates' weights
        for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
            in >> chocolates[i];
        }
       
        int i = 0;  // Pointer for Irina
        int j = N - 1;  // Pointer for Mihaela
        long long Irina_weight = 0;
        long long Mihaela_weight = 0;
        long long min_diff = std::numeric_limits<long long>::max();

        // Move two pointers towards each other
        while (i < j) {
            if (Irina_weight <= Mihaela_weight) {
                Irina_weight += chocolates[i];
                i++;
            } else {
                Mihaela_weight += chocolates[j];
                j--;
            }
            if (i <= j) {
                long long current_diff = std::abs(Irina_weight - Mihaela_weight);
                if (current_diff < min_diff) {
                    min_diff = current_diff;
                }
            }
        }

        // Output the minimum difference
        out << min_diff << '\n';
    }

    // Close files
    in.close();
    out.close();
    
    return 0;
}
```

This updated solution should now correctly calculate the minimal difference between the total amounts of chocolates consumed by Irina and Mihaela for requirement 2, while still satisfying requirement 1.
